#OnThisDay Justice Thurgood Marshall was sworn into the U.S. Supreme Court, becoming the first African-American Supreme Court Justice.
Once again, @HouseDemocrats are working hard at putting people over politics and putting Americans first in avoiding a costly and irresponsible government shutdown.
Simply Put -- the American people deserve better. Democrats are hard at work to keep the government open and put people over politics.

Heartbroken to hear about the passing of Senator Dianne Feinstein. Her dedication to public service and tireless advocacy for Americans has left an everlasting mark on our nation. Our thoughts are with her family, friends, and the American people during this difficult time.

Americans can't afford the adverse impacts of a prolonged government shutdown. It's crucial to put aside partisan differences and collaborate to maintain essential services for all. #PeopleOverPolitics
During the Financial Services Committee Hearing, we highlighted the significant consequences of a government shutdown. It is crucial that we work together to protect the American people.
Was proud to attend the Black Women’s Agenda luncheon during CBCF ALC week last week.
What a wonderful day! There was standing room only today in my CBCF ALC panel today on wealth creation and uplifting Black Americans.
It felt great to kick off the CBCF Annual Legislative Conference with the inaugural NPHC Town Hall panel today.
Proud to see @StateDepartment recognize several HBCUs as Fulbright HBCU Institutional Leaders. The future generation of diplomats look very bright!
Thank you to the Ripon Society for honoring me so the Eighth Annual Roosevelt Leadership Awards.

Wishing all those celebrating Rosh Hashanah a delighted and prosperous new year. May this sweet beginning bring us the determination, kindness, courage, and strength we need to face any challenges ahead. L'shana tova!
#HispanicHeritageMonth is a time to celebrate the contributions that Latinos make to our nation every day.
September 15th marks National POW/MIA Recognition Day. Today, we remember the debt we owe to them and their families.

Before the @CFPB was created, financial institutions saddled consumers w/predatory & discriminatory loans that ultimately crashed our entire economy in 2008. We can’t go backwards. We need a strong #CFPB to keep consumers & our financial system safe! #HandsOffTheCFPB #DefendCFPB

Black communities and other communities of color bore the brunt of the economic pain from the 2008 financial crisis, widening the racial wealth gap. Democrats will continue fighting for a financial system that works for all and #protectconsumers from Wall Street’s greed.

On this day in 1963, four young girls were killed when the 16th Street Baptist Church in Birmingham, Alabama, was bombed by white supremacist domestic terrorists.

Carol Denise McNair. Carole Robertson. Addie Mae Collins. Cynthia Wesley. 

Say their names & never forget.

I was honored to host a roundtable discussion about the World Bank Evolution Roadmap. At a time when the global landscape is rapidly changing, we must ensure that the World Bank adapts to meet the challenges of today. @WorldBank @FSCDems

I am deeply saddened to hear about the tragic loss of my colleague @Rep_Peltola’s husband, Eugene. I send my uplifting prayers and steadfast support to the Peltola family and loved ones during this insufferable time.

22 years after our nation mourned a horrible and major loss, I join with the #OH03 constituents & all Americans in honoring the victims, survivors, families, service members, veterans, allies, & countless Americans whose lives have been forever changed by the 9/11 terror attacks.

September is Ovarian Cancer Awareness Month. During this time, we aim to raise awareness about the risks and prevention of this disease, advocate for increased scientific research, and strive towards finding a cure.

#OnThisDay in 1965, the United States Department of Housing and Urban Development was founded. 

With the mission of creating strong, sustainable, inclusive communities and quality affordable homes for all, HUD was created to take action!
Enjoyed a lovely evening and dinner after meeting with President Kagame.
I was excited to learn about the coffee bean process from a woman owned coffee shop in Rwanda. We even had a graduation, and the coffee was wonderful.

Enjoyed my time in Israel where I’ve joined my colleagues for meetings as we convene on ways to strengthen the U.S.-Israel relationship.

September is a special month dedicated to raising awareness about childhood cancer. We hope that by continuing to research and treat this disease, we can make a difference in the lives of those impacted by childhood cancer.

1 in 7 men in the U.S. will be diagnosed with prostate cancer in their lifetime.

This #PCAM, I encourage all men to #StepUp & talk with their doctor about prostate cancer.

On this #LaborDay, let us acknowledge America's union workers' remarkable and often overlooked contributions. Unions have played a crucial role in shaping our nation and will continue to lead the charge in building a brighter future for America.

September marks the start of #HungerActionMonth! Food shouldn’t be an impossible choice. For millions of people in America, a daily meal isn’t a choice between dishes, it’s a choice between food and other crucial needs. Help end hunger by donating, fundraising, and volunteering!
#WorldSuicidePreventionDay starts with all of us! If you or a loved one are in need of help you can call or text 988 to be connected to a trained crisis counselor. #YouAreNotAlone

Approximately 100,000 Americans are affected by sickle cell disease. During #SickleCellAwarenessMonth, I urge everyone to donate blood and find out your sickle cell status from your local general practitioner!
Thank you so much for a lovely evening, @VP! It was a pleasure to fellowship with several fellow Black women in elected leadership, as well as those running for office including @PeopleforParker

Elated to join my colleagues today to honor the 60th anniversary of the historic March on Washington. Even today, we continue to march for freedom, justice, jobs, and democracy. The stakes are still high as we fight systemic racism and other systems of oppression.
It was a pleasure speaking at Columbus Public Heath event on Undesigning the Redline. I shared my own history of the impacts of redlining and what I’ve done in the Congress to combat it for Ohioans.
Great to see my friend Ed Gordon on the Vineyard. Wishing you a very Happy Birthday, @edlgordon, today!

I will never stop fighting to lower costs and grow the working families in Ohio.

I had a great time yesterday continuing with Ghana Fest Ohio activities and at the Summer Jam. Great to see you @mayorginther and @mayorcoleman.

Celebrating Kid Cudi, a trailblazer in music and an inspiration to millions! As we honor #BMM, let's acknowledge his incredible artistry. Thank you, @KidCudi, for fearlessly carving your path and shaping the sound of a generation.

I was honored to celebrate Juneteenth this year both back home in Cbus, as well as at the White House. Let us use today--and everyday--as a reminder of not only this triumph, but also the continued collective fight for enduring racial justice, pluralism, and equality. #FreedomDay
Juneteenth is more than just a celebration of freedom to commemorate the emancipation of enslaved African-Americans in the United States--it is a triumph for all human rights for the global stage.

Proud to march in the annual pride parade in Cbus to show enduring support to the LGBTQIA+ community. Our collective humanity depends on unity, equality, and a will to understand our collective stories and successes. Thank you to all who participated today! #PrideMonth

Thank you for your brilliance and unwavering spirit!
